The trick with worldbuilding, IMHO, is doing little of it. You spend time, you spend effort, you create things that can paint you into corners later, and at best you make decisions that you could've made at a time when you'd know why that decision matters.

Worldbuilding is painting details before blocking in the canvas. I feel one's better off focusing on the broad setting, what makes this world turn, before zooming in.

Case in point, I just pulled out of my ass an outline with lots of open ends and decision points that flow together. If I had pre-decided what kind of event is at the tavern, or the bird's condition, or what services Tom would be hired to provide before thinking about the scene, a lot of those options may have been foreclosed by Worldbuilding in details that weren't yet important. But instead I thought, "What would be the best way for Bird and Tom to meet that would give them something to bond about?" and him being the only man in town whom she can turn to to fulfill her needs (food, and hopefully discretion) gives me for free the opening scene and it informs how they can reconnect later. Plus it is a chance for some humor by letting Rod think he's bringing the news of the day, unaware that Tom's already met the bird. That gives us dramatic irony as the mood by which we receive Rod's character instead of as Plot Establishment Delivery Man.

It's like the difference between trimming a banzai tree into the most beautiful tree it can be, versus trying to make a banzai tree out of cut and bent up crafting pipe cleaners. You get a better result by pruning after letting the tree do the work naturally than by imagining what it "should" be and then trying to shape something into that. As Mike said, the sculpture is already in the marble.
